Summary: Asteroseismology is a powerful method to determine surface gravities, masses, radii and ages of solar-type stars, and has become the "gold-standard" for calibrating more indirect methods. Here we propose TESS 2-minute cadence observations that will quadruple the current sample of solar-type stars with asteroseismic data, providing fundamental parameters for thousands of stars across the southern hemisphere. The sample will allow us to (i) determine the accuracy of asteroseismic scaling relations, (ii) precisely characterize exoplanets through their host stars and (iii) investigate mode excitation for hot solar-type stars. Our benchmark sample will also enable a wide range of ancillary science including fundamental calibrations of stellar granulation, spectroscopy, and gyrochronology.
